VRA Section 2 Analysis-Los Angeles

DRAFTâ€“Internal Use Only

5/28/2021

Initial Analysis of VRA Section 2 assessment is to check the race/ethnicity of the current county sup district to get a baseline of minority VAP/CVAP from 2010. If the minority population hasnâ€™t decreased, then we need to at least keep the same number of minority opportunity districts as last time.

Steps

  1. Get race/eth summary by sup district from 2010.
  2. Compare race/eth summary from 2010 to race/eth summary from most recent estimates (2019 ACS). See what kind of population change weâ€™ve had.
  3. Determine how many minority opportunity districts you can create where the race/ethnicity share is 50%+.

Step 1: Identify 2010 Minority Opportunity Districts

Which current LA County Supervisorial Districts had 50% or more of minority Voting Age (VAP) or Citizen Voting Age Population (CVAP) in 2010?

  • Supervisorial District 1 (SELA/SGV) is the only district where the Latinx CVAP exceeds 50%.

  • No other districts have majority minority CVAP, although District 2 (South LA) is predominately Black, with 37.2% of the CVAP (followed by Latinx with 32.7% of total CVAP).

Step 2: Identify Population Changes from 2011

How has the Citizen Voting Age Population Changed?

  • The Latinx share of total CVAP has increased in every supervisorial district since 2010.

  • The Black (non-Latinx) share of total CVAP remained steady in all districts except District 2, where it decreased.

  • The Asian (non-Latinx) share of CVAP increased slightly in every supervisorial district since 2010.

  • Although there was some fluctuation in CVAP over the past decade, the AIAN (non-Latinx) and NHPI (non-Latinx) share of total CVAP remained mostly steady in all districts. Neither have increased enough to allow a majority district.

Closer look at the changesâ€¦

  • The Latinx CVAP share increased by 8.4 percentage points in District 2, the district with the largest Latinx CVAP increase.

  • The Asian CVAP share increased the most in Districts 5 and 4, by more than 1.5 percentage points in both.

  • The Black CVAP share decreased by nearly 7 percentage points in District 2.

County CVAP Changes

Step 3: Given the current CVAP, how many minority opportunity districts can be created?

What is the ideal total population per district?

  • According to the HaystaqDNA projections, the 2020 LA County population is 10,138,940.

  • Dividing the LA County total population by 5 Supervisorial Districts, the ideal district population is 2,027,788.
